ncorporating avant-garde expressionist staging, mass chant, agitprop and modernist dramaturgy, Eight Men Speak exemplified the vanguardist aesthetics of the Communist left in the years before the Popular Front. It is the first instance of the collective theatrical techniques that would become widespread in subsequent decades and formative in the development of modern Canadian drama. These include a decentred narrative, collaborative authorship and a refusal of dramaturgical linearity in favour of theatricalist demonstration. As such it is one of the most significant Canadian plays of the first half of the century, and, on the evidence of the surviving photograph of the mise-en-scene, one of the earliest examples of modernist staging in Canada.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aCanadian dramaxHistory and criticismx20th centuryxPolitical plays. 0aCanadian dramay20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aPolitical plays, CanadianxHistory and criticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Drama.2bisacsh1 aCecil-Smith, Edward, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aFilewod, Alan, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGoldberg, Mildred, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2012z978311127413308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2012z978311127716540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780776620749423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780776620749/original  a978-3-11-127413-3  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2012b2012  a978-3-11-127716-5  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2012b2012  aGBV-deGruyter-alles